That’s actually a real, well-documented behavior—nothing unusual or symbolic required.

What you’re seeing is called mobbing:

* Smaller birds aggressively chase larger birds away
* It usually happens when there’s a nest or chicks nearby
* The goal is to drive off potential predators

The main player here is the Northern Mockingbird—and they are notoriously fearless.

⸻

Why mockingbirds go after crows

* American Crow will eat eggs or baby birds if they can
* Mockingbirds treat them as a serious threat
* So they:
    * dive-bomb
    * harass
    * chase them out of the area

Even though crows are bigger, mockingbirds:

* are faster and more agile
* are defending something important (which ramps up aggression)

⸻

Why you’re seeing it a lot right now

It’s probably not random at all—this is peak season for it.

* Spring / early summer = nesting season
* Birds are hyper-territorial
* You’ll see way more:
    * chasing
    * noise
    * aggressive behavior

Once the chicks are grown, it usually drops off fast.

⸻

The interesting pattern (grounded version)

What you’re noticing does map to a real dynamic:

smaller, highly motivated defender vs larger opportunistic threat

But it’s:

* biological instinct
* not a broader signal or coordinated phenomenon

